Every school day parents dropping off & picking up their children from Sunset View Elementary School park in any available space including against red curbs. Red curbs most often parked in are on the 4200 block of Hill St. & the 900 block of Moana Dr.. Red curbs in this area are on corners and in front of both a mailbox & a fire hydrant. Parking violations are also rampant immediately outside the school. School starts at 9 am M-F with children being dropped off as early as 8:30 and school is dismissed at 3:35 each day except for the half-day on Thursdays which is dismissed at 12:45. In addition to the violations mentioned, it is a common practice to block driveways in the neighborhood. These parking habits create a dangerous environment for neighbors trying to negotiate their own neighborhood, but also a hazard to pedestrians/students trying to cross streets. This problem is compounded by the Point Loma Nazarene University students illegally exiting their campus onto Moana Dr. where they exceed the 25 mph.

Hello - I want to report a potential hazard due to the timing of the light at this intersection. I have almost been hit at least three times, including today. The issue is that pedestrians crossing on the south west end of this intersection are not easily visible to cars that are turning left from Pangea Drive. I think there are several reasons for this that are out of the city's control (lots of plants on that side that act as shade and hide the pedestrian and also the location of the pedestrian is blinded by the car's left front pillar), but it will help if the timing for the pedestrian walk signal occurs before the light turns green for cars that are turning left. I crossed today and I could tell that the car that was coming towards me did not initially see me or even while I was crossing, so I ran. I looked back at her and it still appears she did not see me. Apologies if this is confusing, but please feel free to call me at 9517642006. This has happened many times and I am concerned someone will get hit.

Re Get-It_Done report # 00303797 which I believe has been closed prematurely. I first reported this problem in March 2018. Work was being done at the time to curb-side storm drains just down the hill near Park Village Road; perhaps this report was erroneously closed in association with that work? My concern is with a storm drain cover (access point? whatever one calls the round things in the middle of the road, not at the curb). This one sits significantly below the level of the asphalt and has gotten deeper with the passage of time. It's right where three lanes merge into two. Depending on traffic it is sometimes impossible to swerve to avoid driving through it and it gives a serious jolt. Several months ago, well before the start of the rainy season, it appeared that someone might have tried to fill the space with dry concrete mix but it was gradually dispersed by traffic, perhaps the action of a frustrated resident. Please reevaluate this location. P.S. there is no good category match for this problem.

public_description: This group of Homeless people have had a camp set up since before 12-25-18. They are a public nuisance in every way. They can be heard screaming all hours of the day and night including right now. They use the trees and private fence as a bathroom. They brush their teeth and shower in the bushes in addition to the bathroom even though free public facilities are 300 yards away. I have seen several fights amongst them and with civilians walking their dogs. They use alcohol and drugs and leave trash everywhere. They pull the trash out of the dumpster and public trash cans every day looking for cans and never put the trash back in the receptacle. The highly aggressive/confrontational behavior makes it uncomfortable for our complex to take their children and pets down to the grass especially at night. We would like to remain anonymous as they would likely become aggressive with our tenants. I believe the San Diego municipal code states it is unlawful to camp on any beach or in public parks.

This light combination backs up every morning. It could be addressed in a couple ways: either by changing the timing of this light with respect to the next light north (@ Soledad Mtn Rd / La Jolla Scenic Dr) or by ENFORCING traffic laws. In specific, vehicles turning left from Nautilus onto La Jolla Scenic consistently pull into the intersection before their way out is clear, thus causing northbound vehicles on La Jolla Scenic to have to wait for them to clear before passing the intersection. This can take some time due to the timing of the light at Soledad Mtn Rd/La Jolla Scenic. It also slows the passage of southbound vehicles turning left onto Cardeno Dr. This means that only about 1/3 of the time the light is green is safe for cars to use the intersection. It also leads to cars dangerously whipping up the right turn lane and then cutting back into the straight lane, again causing backups. This happens every day and is incredibly frustrating for law-abiding drivers who experience severe delays.

On Thursday 02/14/2019, an issue with the storm drain led to excessive flooding in the area around it when it started raining. No warning signs were placed and my car (Burgundy 1992 Honda Civic), which was parked near the drain, became submerged in water. The water managed to flood the passenger side of my car. After the water finally drained, I needed to take my car to the nearest car wash or else mold was going to start forming. I'm reporting this in order to at least get reimbursed for the detailing job. Problems with the engine and transmission have not arisen yet, but I'm keeping a close eye the next few days to make sure there is no long term damage.

The two trees belonging to the owners of 2731 Glenwick Place, La Jolla, CA, 92037, are an immediate safety and health hazard. The two trees severely overhang on Glenwick Lane and have a mere clearance of 6? in many areas. The result is that two lanes of traffic can no longer pass on this two-way street causing cars to swerve at the last second and nearly crash. When larger cars pass by, the branches collide with their car resulting in a very dangerous incident. Furthermore, we we were notified by the trash and recycling company that the trash and recycling belonging to surrounding homes will no longer be picked up as the truck cannot pass by. Most concerning of all, the tree debris and dirt pours clogs the storm drain and causes standing water. The result is flooding and mosquitos which cause West Nile virus. These dangerous factors are in immediately health and safety hazard to the surrounding community. We have contacted the homeowner several times and they are not willing to work towards a solution.

The pedestrian light across Alvarado activates at the same time as the Green Light for Reservoir. The problem is that, because Reservoir ends at this intersection, a green light means that drivers must turn left or right. Since pedestrians have the right of way when the walk light is on, they are at risk of being struck by a driver who is turning and not checking for pedestrians. CalTrans has recently been making pedestrian safety a paramount concern, and this mistiming of the pedestrian walk light and the green light for Reservoir could put pedestrians in serious danger, particularly if drivers are not paying attention. Please address this potential safety issue.

A City storm drain behind and above our property, and adjoining Whispering Ridge Homeowners Association (WRHOA) property, is situated at the top of a high ridge on Fairbrook Road. This City storm drain diverts street storm water from Fairbrook Road and dumps it onto the open slope directly behind our property. The resulting flow of storm water comes down with great force and has eroded the slope, creating a deep open gully through which the storm water rapidly flows and moves rocks, debris and mud down the hillside. This whole mess runs into horizontal culverts on WRHOA property for collection into a drainage pipe/ head wall installed by the City on and under our property at 12403 Kingspine Avenue. This has caused flooding on our property when it becomes clogged and blocked at its entry point with mud, rock and debris brought down after heavy rain by the storm water. WE NEED ACCUMULATED MUD, ROCKS AND DEBRIS REMOVED AND A SOLUTION TO THIS RECURRING SERIOUS PROBLEM DUE TO POOR DRAINAGE DESIGN. NEED SITE VISIT.
